THE popular Kwagga and Kanyables Jazz Pub has entertained residents and visitors in KwaNobuhle kasi, Uitenhage for the past 13 years. But from now on, no more alcohol will be sold, as born again Nokukhanya Xangati will turn the boozers&rsquo; paradise into a venue to host weddings, kids&rsquo; parties and conferences.&ldquo;It&rsquo;s part of celebrating my 42th birthday, as I was born on 3 February.&rdquo; Nokukhanya ran the business with her brother Kwagga Xangati (60).At the pub, patrons enjoyed live jazz on Sundays by musicians such as McCoy Mrubata, the late Stompie Mavi, Blaze, the Yankee Brothers and Mo Jazz.&ldquo;Business was booming and people were in and out of this building.&rdquo; &ldquo;But now I want to curb the boozing. &ldquo;My parents never boozed and I want to honour their legacy,&rdquo; she said, adding that her parents built a school out of mud and employed 10 teachers in Nciya, near Kirkwood.Ward 47 Councillor Nontuthuzelo Skweyiya said she supports the new venture.